      About this item

      • SMART OUTLET CONTROL: Seamlessly control your appliances, lights, and electronics from anywhere with the Geeni Smart Wi-Fi Outlet. Use voice commands with Alexa and Google Assistant, or control through the Geeni app for effortless smart home management.
      • VERSATILE FUNCTIONALITY FOR EVERY ROOM: The Geeni Smart Wi-Fi Outlet is designed to fit any standard outlet, allowing you to manage multiple devices across different rooms. Its user-friendly interface makes it easy to integrate into your home for enhanced convenience.
      • ENERGY MONITORING & SCHEDULING: Monitor your energy usage in real-time with the Geeni app. Set schedules and timers for your connected devices, optimizing power consumption and lowering your energy bills.
      • REMOTE ACCESS & VOICE CONTROL: Control your home from anywhere, whether you're at home or on the go. Turn appliances on/off remotely or use voice commands via Alexa or Google Assistant for hands-free convenience.
      • SMART HOME COMPATIBILITY: The Geeni Smart Outlet is compatible with Alexa, Google Assistant, and the Geeni app, making it a versatile addition to any smart home setup. Ideal for managing lights, fans, and other household devices.

          • Why won't my plug connect to my WiFi?

            Double-check your Wi-Fi password and internet connection. If the signal is weak, reset your router and try again.

          • What kind of WiFi does my house need for Geeni products?

            Geeni products work best with 2.4GHz WiFi for wider coverage and compatibility. Ensure your router supports this band.

          • How do I activate the 2.4GHz band on my router?

            Access your router settings through its IP address, log in, go to Advanced Settings > Network Settings, and enable the 2.4GHz band.

          • Can these smart plugs be controlled by Amazon Echo & Google Home?

            Yes, Geeni smart plugs and other power devices work with Amazon Echo and Google Home.

          • Should I have Bluetooth on when connecting my product?

            Enable Bluetooth and location on your smartphone for a smooth setup.

          How customer reviews and ratings work

          Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

          To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

          Amazon Customer
          3 out of 5 stars
          Seems to Require a Constant Connection
          Admittedly I used this for a task that could be fulfilled with old mechanical timers and I actually replaced three of these with old mechanical timers to great results. - I installed 3 of these in my home to 3 different lamps. - I setup two triggers per day. One to turn them on and one to turn them off. - I have Viasat Satellite internet that has very high uptime, except during storms, but has very high latency. I actually don't know the top end, but I'm guessing it's anywhere from 600-1500ms low-high.At first, these would run for a couple weeks faithfully turning the lamps on and off, but then randomly they'd get disconnected from the wifi. When this happens they would not reconnect. They would not run any scheduled triggers and the only solution is to unplug and replug the outlet, wait for it to hopefully reconnect and then trigger the lamp on manually with the app, since it would have already missed it's scheduled trigger. I dealt with this every week or two for awhile, but truth be told even this is unacceptable. Eventually they started disconnecting every day even when my ViaSat was not data capped.I reached out to Geeni support, but when I explained my internet situation, they didn't even want to look into it. It seems that they realize this is an issue and that there will be no helping me.So my partner and I discussed it and realized that the mechanical timer outlets that I wanted to avoid, would actually result in far less hassle. We switched all 3 of these for mechanical timers and haven't had a problem since.Feedback to Geeni and to potential buyers:Why should a "smart" outlet behave this way?1. Shouldn't we expect an outlet that has disconnected from the wifi/internet, for whatever reason, to eventually reconnect on it's own without needing to be re-plugged?2. Shouldn't we expect a "smart" device to be smart enough to remember a couple of triggers per day and continue operating on them even if it loses internet connectivity?3. Lastly, I checked the internet usage on these and found that a single plug was using over 6% of our entire internet usage (see image)(if true, that would be 3.8GB per month). I'm not sure I trust this usage to be accurate as it's so outrageous, but it definitely makes me wonder what the internet usage is .
